{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"be25a204-e208-4884-942f-cd867ad02022","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll create the GitHub Actions workflow for trusted publishing. This requires two parts: a workflow file and configuration on nuget.org.","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_o5V9DgANTnouMFj0YaZeSj","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /tmp/sv-f90114563e954737b63c63dbfd1378cd/.github/workflows","description":"Create workflows directory","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Create workflows directory"}],"interactionId":"3e2a7f8a-ad86-4de7-bd6c-17e5860753b2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. The user says they have a .NET class library at `src/MyLib/MyLib.csproj` but it doesn't exist yet in this directory. Let me help them set up the GitHub Actions workflow for trusted publishing. I'll create the necessary directory structure and workflow file.\n\nFor NuGet trusted publishing (OIDC), I need to:\n1. Create a GitHub Actions workflow that:\n   - Builds and packs the library\n   - Uses `dotnet nuget push` with `--source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json`\n   - Uses the OIDC token for authentication\n\n\n2. The workflow requires `permissions: id-token: write` to request an OIDC token from GitHub, which then gets passed as the API key to authenticate with NuGet.org. On the NuGet.org side, they'll need to register a trusted publisher linking their GitHub repository and workflow file. So the OIDC token flow is: GitHub issues a token, nuget.org exchanges it for an API key, then that key authenticates the push command. The workflow just needs the `id-token: write` permission and the right `dotnet nuget push` command pointing to the official NuGet source with the token as the API key.\n\nSetting up the workflow with permissions and the push command... I'm realizing NuGet.org's trusted publishing setup requires configuring the publisher on their site first—specifying the repo owner, name, workflow file, and optionally an environment—then in the GitHub Actions workflow, I'd use an OIDC token instead of a static API key for authentication when pushing the package. I'm not entirely certain about the exact action name for the NuGet token exchange, so I'll go with the well-documented approach that uses `id-token: write` permission and the OIDC token directly with `dotnet nuget push`. I'll create both the workflow file and setup instructions to make this practical and working.","outputTokens":1861,"requestId":"A40D:2D0E:108041B:12FAC96:69F93F85"},"id":"95679a73-c84e-414a-ad66-1d7e3b8eff63","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:53:56.962Z","parentId":"9e7f3b0f-67ba-45ac-bc66-76aa8ac21cd7"}
