{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0ef8526d-a79e-4dc1-9b40-ed6680c88d47","content":"Here's the workflow I created at `.github/workflows/publish.yml`. It triggers on version tags (`v*`), builds/packs your library, and pushes to nuget.org using OIDC — no API key needed.\n\n**To complete setup, configure nuget.org:**\n\n1. Go to **nuget.org → Manage Packages → [your package] → Trusted Publishers** (or for new packages: Account Settings → Trusted Publishers)\n2. Add a GitHub Actions trusted publisher with:\n   - **Repository owner:** `myorg`\n   - **Repository name:** `mylib`\n   - **Workflow filename:** `publish.yml`\n   - **Environment:** `nuget-publish`\n\n**On GitHub:**\n\n3. Create a repository environment named `nuget-publish` (Settings → Environments). Optionally add protection rules (required reviewers, deployment branches restricted to tags).\n\n**To publish:**\n\n```bash\ngit tag v1.0.0\ngit push origin v1.0.0\n```\n\nKey points:\n- `id-token: write` permission enables the OIDC token exchange\n- The `environment: nuget-publish` must match what you register on nuget.org\n- No `--api-key` is passed to `dotnet nuget push` — the OIDC token is used automatically via the GitHub Actions runtime\n- The environment adds a security boundary (only workflows in that environment can push)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3e2a7f8a-ad86-4de7-bd6c-17e5860753b2","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"A403:56360:142E3F5:16A09CA:69F93FAA"},"id":"1d41078d-764d-4bfe-9719-7a081a6b8122","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:54:10.269Z","parentId":"9743fe3c-eab9-4449-9cbe-d5fda09fc195"}
